I found several relevant search results about iOS 18 SwiftUI toolbar liquid glass appearance and grouped items. Here are the key findings:

## Toolbar Updates with Liquid Glass

Toolbars changed significantly in Liquid Glass with a new glassy background and the ability to be split into groups. The toolbar API doesn't change much and takes the Liquid Glass look and feel without any code changes.

## Grouping Toolbar Items

The new Liquid Glass provides toolbar grouping functionality, allowing you to group secondary actions together by splitting them from primary actions. SwiftUI introduced the new ToolbarSpacer type allowing developers to split toolbar items and place space between them, with support for both fixed and flexible spacing.

## Design Guidelines

When organizing a toolbar, buttons should be grouped by function and frequency of use, and text-labeled buttons should be placed apart from symbol-based buttons to avoid confusion.

## Automatic Glass Styling

When buttons are placed inside a SwiftUI Toolbar, SwiftUI may automatically render them with glass styles depending on placement and context, and in many cases these buttons are styled as glass by default.

The search results indicate this is primarily an iOS 26 feature (part of "Liquid Glass"), though some sources mention iOS 18. The implementation allows for sophisticated grouping using `ToolbarItemGroup` and `ToolbarSpacer` to create visually cohesive toolbar layouts with the new glass aesthetic.

Based on the search results, here are the key ways to make the tab bar more transparent or less visible in SwiftUI on iOS 18:

## Using `.toolbarBackground()` Modifier

You can use `.toolbarBackground(.hidden, for: .tabBar)` on the view you are presenting in the tab to control the tab bar visibility.(no content)For hiding the tab bar's background, apply `.toolbarBackground(.hidden, for: .tabBar)` to the first tab.

## Adjusting Transparency with Color Opacity

You can change the background to a translucent color using `.toolbarBackground(Color.orange.opacity(0.8), for: .tabBar)` - simply adjust the opacity value to make it more transparent.

## Important Notes

The default is `.automatic` which makes the background visible when scroll bar content is behind it.(no content)The color set in the toolbarBackground modifier doesn't always show and can be invisible based on the system style. To ensure your transparency settings are applied, you may need to force a tab bar to always visible by setting `.toolbar(.visible, for: .tabBar)`.

## Example Code Pattern

```swift
TabView {
    YourView()
        .tabItem {
            Label("Tab", systemImage: "icon")
        }
        .toolbarBackground(.hidden, for: .tabBar) // Makes it transparent
        // OR
        .toolbarBackground(Color.white.opacity(0.3), for: .tabBar) // Custom transparency
}
```

The `.toolbarBackground()` modifier is the modern SwiftUI approach available in iOS 16 and later, which should work well for iOS 18.
